Static data structures â€” data collections in memory that are of
fixed size.
b
A classic example is a fixed size array in C++:
Data within data structures are stored in the form of
pointers
b
to the correct location of the data in computer memory. Pointers are bit strings, representing a memory address, that can themselves be stored in memory.

Static data structures allocate chunks of memory to store their items within. For example, the array I instantiated above allocates 5 x 15 chunks of empty memory which I can then overwrite with values, as so:
Primitive data types are data types that
make up data structures.
b

An example of a primitive data type in C++ is the integer, which is built into the language and can be used to construct more complex data structures â€” such as the aforementioned fixed array of integers. Primitives, unlike fundamental structures, can
only hold one type of data
b
, and can
hold only one value at a time
b

Fundamental data structures are a level more complex, and are always built upon primitive data types. Examples of fundamental data types include arrays, dynamic lists, dictionaries, tuples, and strings.
Advantages and disadvantages of fundamental data structures
In order to enumerate the advantages and disadvantages of data structures, we must first discuss the most common types of data structures that are used:
Fixed-size lists
b

(e.g arrays) â€” have the advantage of being extremely fast to operate on. Additionally, each index in the array can be accessed in O(1) time, which means that the speed at which items within the array can be accessed is the same regardless of the size of the array. Thus, arrays are extremely useful for containing
large amounts of data
b
that are
all of the same type
b
, when the size of the data is known and is unchanging.
Dynamically-sized lists
b
(e.g vectors) â€” similar to fixed-sized lists in that they can only store one data type, but has the advantage of being resizable. Theyâ€™re
slower
b
than fixed-sized lists, so they should only be used when the size of data is unknown or mutable. They share all of the indexing advantages of fixed-sized lists.
Hash maps (also known as lookup tables)
b

(e.g unordered maps or python dictionaries) â€” have the advantage of pairing two different types of data together. If your intent is to create a database that pairs numerical descriptors with string names, it might be wise to use a hash map. The largest advantage of a hash map is that it supports
mapping between tow data types
b
while still supporting arbitrary access of any element within it in constant time.
Stacks â€”
b
only support three main operations:
pull
b
push
b
, and
see_first
b

. Imagine a stack as a stack of papers; itâ€™s possible to add more papers onto the top of the stack or to remove papers from the top of the stack, but itâ€™s not possible to read papers that are in the middle of the stack without removing papers above them first. Stacks are
extremely fast but extremely limited in operations,
b
so theyâ€™re suited for algorithms where the most recent data points are always retrieved first (e.g depth-first-search).
Queues â€”
b
can be thought of as the inverse of stacks. Data points can be added onto the back of a queue, and can be removed from the front of a queue. Like stacks, queues are
extremely fast and computationally efficient
b

. Useful for simulations that use queues as models, or algorithms that require accessing the oldest stored data first. As with a stack, itâ€™s impossible to look at the items in the middle of a queue without traversing all of the items ahead of it first, so if
arbitrary index access is necessary, a list is preferred over a queue.
b
Heaps â€”
b
use a mathematical trick to ensure that either the minimum or the maximum of the data stored in the heap can be accessed in constant time. Very useful if we need to find the
maximum or the minimum of the stored data extremely quickly
b

(e.g, if we want to find the cheapest deal out of a million possible products to purchase on Amazon). Its weakness comes from the fact that accessing any item other than the minimum or maximum takes O(logN) time, which is far slower than accessing an arbitrary item in a list.
Records â€”
b
Table-like data structures that can store mixed types of data. As shown below, different columns can contain different data types. Records are extremely useful for
storing real-world data
b
, which is often of mixed type.
Static arrays
b

â€” Statically declared arrays are allocated an appropriate amount of memory based on their size at compile time. Their sizes are unable to be changed later, and attempting to access an index of a statically declared array that is outside the size of the array may lead to runtime errors.
At compile time, itâ€™s mandatory to declare both the type and the size of the statically declared array.
Records
b

Lookup tables â€” Lookup tables are represented internally in C++ as hash maps. The key of the lookup table is converted via a
hash function
b
into an integer index of a large dynamically-sized array, which then contains the item corresponding to the key of the hash map.

Vectors â€” C++ vectors are statically sized arrays that have their contents copied over to a larger array whenever the vector is resized and extra space is needed. This maintains the ability of the vectors to access any of their elements in O(1) time, but also allows for dynamic resizing. Unfortunately, this resizing function is quite slow, and thus makes data storage and retrieval from Vectors much slower than from Arrays.
Instantiation â€” memory for the data structure is allocated in memory. If the data structure is
fixed
b
, the memory allocated to it will not change throughout runtime. If the data structure is dynamic, more memory is allocated to it on the fly as necessary.
Insertion, deletion, replacement â€” insertion, deletion, and replacement is fairly simple when it comes to
fundamental data structures
b

. Inserting, deleting, or replacing elements of an array or a dynamically sized list involves accessing the desired index and replacing the current memory contents of that index with either new content (in the case of insertion or replacement) or emptying it (in the case of deletion).
In the case of a
queue, heap, or stack
b

, insertion, deletion, and replacement are more complex and require traversing the data structure from top to bottom until the desired point in order to add, remove, or replace the desired data element.
Searching through an array, stack, queue, heap, or dynamically-sized list involves
iterating through all of its elements
b
until the right one is found. For records, searching is simpler and involves passing in the desired key to the hash function to access the correct memory location within the hash map.
Size determination is done
automatically
b
by most programming languages by the use of a
size counter
b

. For example, each vector in C++ keeps a tally of the current number of items within it, and that tally will be incremented every time a new item is inserted into it. This way, the size can be accessed at any time rapidly, without having to count the number of items within the data structure every time its current size needs to be known.

Copying a data structure involves creating another data structure of the same type and size, and copying every memory index from the original data structure into the new one. Most languages support two types of copying:
deep and shallow
b
. Deep copying involves the complete copying of every memory index, while shallow copying only copies the
memory pointers
b
of the original data structure to the new data structure. Shallow copying is faster, but
modifying the original data structure may lead to modifications in the copied data structure
b
Comparing two structures of the same type
Comparing two structures of the same type involves:
Checking whether the sizes are equal.
Checking whether all the items within the two data structures are equal.
If both of the above are satisfied, the two data structures are considered equal.
